export const FAQ = "# The ARCHV app: support knowledge base\n\nThe single source of truth the L1 support agent answers from. Written in the brand voice:\nBritish, warm, plain, no em dashes. Each entry has the answer to give the user and a note on\nwhether L1 can close it or must escalate.\n\nScope reminder: the app has no login. Saves and reading history live on the device. The only\nthings stored on our servers are anonymous support tickets and, if the user opted in, a push\ntoken. There is no personal profile, no email unless the user volunteers one.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Is this an official FIFA, club, or player app?\n\nNo. The ARCHV is an independent football publication. The portraits are original illustrations,\nnot photographs, made for commentary and reporting. We are not affiliated with, endorsed by, or\nlicensed by FIFA, any club, federation, competition, or player.\nL1: resolve.\n\n## 2. I want a refund\n\nPurchases go through Apple, so refunds do too. We cannot issue them from our side. Go to\nreportaproblem.apple.com, sign in with your Apple ID, find the ARCHV purchase, and request a\nrefund. Apple usually decides within a day or two.\nL1: resolve. If the user is upset about a charge they say they never made, escalate to L2.\n\n## 3. I paid for Archv+ but it is not showing, or I got a new phone\n\nOpen Settings inside the app and tap Restore Purchases. Make sure you are signed into the same\nApple ID you bought it with. Archv+ follows your Apple ID, not the device.\nL1: resolve. If restore genuinely fails after that, escalate to L2.\n\n## 4. The daily notification is not arriving\n\nThree things to check. First, iOS Settings, Notifications, The ARCHV, and make sure they are on.\nSecond, the toggle inside the app's own Settings. Third, by design we send at most one a day when\na new story lands, so a quiet news day means no push. If all three are right and nothing comes for\nseveral days, escalate.\nL1: resolve the common cases. Escalate a confirmed multi-day failure to L2.\n\n## 5. Content will not load, or looks out of date\n\nPull down to refresh on any tab. The app reads from thearchv.ca, so a brief connection drop can\nstall it. Your last loaded stories stay readable offline. If a refresh on a good connection still\nshows nothing, escalate.\nL1: resolve. Escalate a persistent blank feed to L2 (it points at a feed problem).\n\n## 6. My saved articles disappeared, or did not move to my new phone\n\nSaves are kept privately on your device, not in an account, because the app has no login. That\nkeeps your reading yours and means there is nothing for anyone to breach. The trade-off is that\nsaves do not travel between devices, and clearing the app's data clears them.\nL1: resolve, with the honest explanation. Do not promise cloud sync.\n\n## 7. Why is there no login or account?\n\nA deliberate choice. You do not hand us an email or a password, so there is nothing of yours for\nus to lose. Saves and history stay on your phone.\nL1: resolve.\n\n## 8. What is Archv+ and how do I cancel?\n\nArchv+ is an optional membership that supports the work and unlocks the extra reading. It is not\na wall around the daily stories, those stay free. Manage or cancel it the same way as any Apple\nsubscription: Settings, your name, Subscriptions, The ARCHV.\nL1: resolve.\n\n## 9. The illustrations, likeness, or an image concern\n\nEvery portrait is original artwork, painted for commentary and reporting, never a traced or\nphotographic image. If someone raises a genuine likeness or rights concern rather than a general\nquestion, treat it as sensitive.\nL1: answer general questions. Escalate any actual rights or likeness complaint straight to L3.\n\n## 10. There is a factual error in a story\n\nThank them, it matters. Take the specifics: which story, which line, and what the correct fact is.\nThis goes to the editorial desk, and corrections are made quickly.\nL1: capture the detail and escalate to L2 for routing to editorial.\n\n## 11. What do you store about me, and can you delete it?\n\nIf they have not contacted support and not opted into notifications, nothing tied to them. A\nsupport ticket holds what they typed plus an anonymous device id. A push opt-in holds a device\ntoken. No name, no email unless they gave one. A deletion request is honoured.\nL1: explain. Escalate an actual deletion request to L3 so it is actioned and recorded.\n\n## 12. The app keeps crashing\n\nMake sure they are on the latest version from the App Store, then fully close and reopen the app.\nWe do receive crash reports automatically, so it may already be in hand. If it keeps happening,\ntake their device model and iOS version.\nL1: resolve the basics. Escalate a reproducible crash with device details to L2.\n\n## 13. Accessibility problem (text size, VoiceOver, contrast)\n\nWe want the app readable for everyone, and it supports larger text and VoiceOver. Get the specific\nscreen and what went wrong.\nL1: capture detail and escalate to L2. Treat accessibility reports as high priority.\n\n---\n\n## Routing rules for the L1 agent\n\n- Resolve when the answer is fully covered above and nothing is disputed.\n- Escalate to L2 for: confirmed feed or push failures, reproducible crashes, restore-purchase\n  failures after the standard steps, factual corrections, accessibility reports.\n- Escalate to L3 (the founder) for anything sensitive: rights or likeness complaints, disputed or\n  fraudulent charges, legal threats, and data deletion requests.\n- When in doubt, escalate rather than guess. A wrong confident answer costs more than a handover.\n- Always reply in the brand voice: warm, brief, British, no em dashes, no false promises.\n";
